oc:kn_1267e87f a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When structuring content for any audience" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Frame content for the audience: executives get outcomes and goals; engineers get technical details and links; customers get benefits not features; partners get dependencies and asks." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Audience-appropriate framing increases comprehension and actionability of the update." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_1403ba32 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When project tracker, chat, meeting transcription, or knowledge base tools are not connected" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If no connected tools are available, ask the user to provide: what was accomplished, current blockers/risks, key decisions made/needed, and what is coming next." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Ensures the skill can still generate useful updates even without automated data sources." .

oc:kn_195d974d a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When making asks in any update" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Asks must be specific and actionable: 'Decision on X by Friday' not 'support needed'. Include who, what, and by when." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Vague asks get vague responses. Specific asks with deadlines drive accountability." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_1acbbb3b a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always — core workflow for generating stakeholder updates" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Determine update type (weekly/monthly/launch/ad-hoc) 2. Determine audience (executive/engineering/cross-functional/customer/board) 3. Pull context from connected tools (project tracker, chat, meeting transcription, knowledge base) or ask user 4. Generate update using audience-specific template 5. Review and offer adjustments for tone, detail, delivery channel" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_216d5080 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When communicating risks in any update" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never present risks without mitigations. Never be vague about risks — specify what, how long, and why. Every risk should come with a plan and a specific ask." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Risks without mitigations create anxiety without action. Specific asks enable stakeholders to help." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_2f2dc198 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating customer or external updates" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Customer-facing updates must contain no internal jargon, no ticket numbers, no technical implementation details. Frame everything as what the customer can now DO, not what was built." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Internal terminology confuses customers and undermines trust. Benefits-focused language drives adoption." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_4020f476 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When documenting architecture or strategic decisions (ADRs)" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "markdown" ;
    oc:directiveContent """# [Decision Title]
## Status
[Proposed / Accepted / Deprecated / Superseded by ADR-XXX]
## Context
What is the situation that requires a decision?
## Decision
What did we decide?
## Consequences
- Positive consequences
- Negative consequences or tradeoffs
- What this enables or prevents
## Alternatives Considered
What other options were evaluated and why rejected?""" .

oc:kn_423ecba3 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating any stakeholder update" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never bury the lead — start with the most important thing. Do not hide bad news after good news." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Decision-makers skim updates; burying critical information causes missed signals and delayed responses." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_42c5c4aa a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating customer/external update" ;
    oc:directiveContent """What's new:
- [Feature] — [Benefit in customer terms]. [How to use].
Coming soon:
- [Feature] — [Expected timing]. [Why it matters].
Known issues:
- [Issue] — [Status]. [Workaround].
Feedback:
- [How to share feedback]""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Coming soon",
        "Feedback",
        "Known issues",
        "What's new" .

oc:kn_69b36a84 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating engineering team update" ;
    oc:directiveContent """Shipped:
- [Feature/fix] — [Link]. [Impact].
In progress:
- [Item] — [Owner]. [Expected completion]. [Blockers].
Decisions:
- [Decision made]: [Rationale]. [ADR link].
- [Decision needed]: [Context]. [Options]. [Rec].
Priority changes:
- [What changed and why]
Coming up:
- [Next items] — [Context]""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Coming up",
        "Decisions",
        "In progress",
        "Priority changes",
        "Shipped" .

oc:kn_766b16d1 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating executive/leadership update" ;
    oc:directiveContent """Status: [Green / Yellow / Red]
TL;DR: [One sentence]
Progress:
- [Outcome tied to goal/OKR]
- [Milestone with impact]
- [Key metric movement]
Risks:
- [Risk]: [Mitigation]. [Ask].
Decisions needed:
- [Decision]: [Options with rec]. Need by [date].
Next milestones:
- [Milestone] — [Date]""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Decisions needed",
        "Next milestones",
        "Progress",
        "Risks",
        "Status",
        "TL;DR" .

oc:kn_b13feba6 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When assigning status color to any update" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Status colors (Green/Yellow/Red) must reflect genuine assessment, not optimism. Yellow is not failure — it is good risk management. Move to Yellow at the FIRST sign of risk." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Inaccurate status colors erode trust and delay intervention. Early Yellow flags give more options." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_b892fd55 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When communicating risks in any update" ;
    oc:directiveContent "To communicate risks effectively: 1. State the risk clearly 2. Quantify the impact 3. State the likelihood 4. Present the mitigation 5. Make a specific ask" ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

oc:kn_d02cf362 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating cross-functional partner update" ;
    oc:directiveContent """What's coming:
- [Feature/launch] — [Date]. [What this means for your team].
What we need from you:
- [Specific ask] — [Context]. By [date].
Decisions made:
- [Decision] — [How it affects your team].
Open for input:
- [Topic] — [How to provide feedback].""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Decisions made",
        "Open for input",
        "What we need from you",
        "What's coming" .

oc:kn_d45a88cb a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When categorizing and managing risks in updates" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the ROAM framework for risk management: Resolved (no longer a concern), Owned (someone actively managing it), Accepted (proceeding without mitigation), Mitigated (reduced to acceptable level)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "ROAM provides a shared vocabulary that makes risk status immediately clear to all stakeholders." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_edbf1b26 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing updates for executives or leadership" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Executive updates must be under 300 words. Engineering updates can be longer but must be structured for skimming." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Executives have limited attention; brevity forces clarity and prioritization." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

